WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.400
My name is Devin, I'm a Solutions Engineer at Posit, and I'm really thrilled to be up

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:16.480
here today to talk about Quarto, because in many ways, the vision of Quarto, that reproducible

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:22.840
research is a core part of high-quality scientific communications, was a key driver in actually

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:28.440
nudging me along my career journey that ultimately has brought me to Posit.

00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:34.119
Almost 10 years ago, as a graduate student, R Markdown blew me away when all of a sudden

00:00:34.119 --> 00:00:39.080
I could shortcut an enormous amount of the tedious interactions from working in R scripts

00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:44.959
and actually taking the outputs of those, getting them into Word or PDF documents to

00:00:44.959 --> 00:00:46.279
distribute.

00:00:46.279 --> 00:00:52.639
Now, as many graduate students are inclined to do, I also dabbled in figuring out how

00:00:52.639 --> 00:01:00.040
I could use the tools I was learning, in particular R, in fun, new ways.

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:05.239
So about that time, a new tool emerged called Gitbook, and it was really fascinating to

00:01:05.239 --> 00:01:09.320
me because the idea was to take a bunch of Markdown documents, jam them through this

00:01:09.320 --> 00:01:15.000
processor, and out popped a website that had navigation and styling, and it kind of looked

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:16.320
like a book.

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:19.680
And so I said, hmm, that seems kind of interesting.

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:25.760
I wonder if I can take R Markdown documents, get them to Markdown to put them through Gitbook.

00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:31.879
And so I put together some really, really scary-looking code, but thankfully the RStudio

00:01:31.879 --> 00:01:40.239
team was also keeping an eye on such ideas, and Bookdown entered the scene.

00:01:40.239 --> 00:01:45.760
This ability to build on a unit of an R Markdown document into more complex content felt like

00:01:45.760 --> 00:01:50.160
a taste of opportunities to come.

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:54.080
And so similarly, when I started playing around with what it was going to be like to build

00:01:54.080 --> 00:02:00.000
a blog, I found Hugo, a static site generator that you could also make most of your content

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:01.000
with Markdown.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:06.800
And so by using that content in Markdown, plus a little bit of metadata and configuration,

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:10.320
you could generate a professional-looking site.

00:02:11.279 --> 00:02:16.600
Again, the RStudio team responded with Blogdown.

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:21.460
And it was so exciting to me, because there's actually official tools to support these janky

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:24.119
workflows that I was trying to come up with.

00:02:24.119 --> 00:02:30.399
That integration between Hugo and Markdown was able to help bring content to life.

00:02:30.399 --> 00:02:36.479
But as fascinating as these experiments were, as fascinating as learning those tools were,

00:02:36.479 --> 00:02:41.440
it was undeniable that there were some significant points of friction and frustration in figuring

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:45.600
it out, especially around the tooling boundaries.

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:49.279
It was never fun to see a Hugo theme that just kind of didn't work for how you wanted

00:02:49.279 --> 00:02:55.119
to lay it out, or something that worked in Bookdown that you couldn't put into Blogdown.

00:02:55.119 --> 00:03:00.800
And so as powerful as these tools were, it was clear that the separation of the communities

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:09.520
that we were trying to meld together left some gaps to make this approachable to everyone.

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:11.800
But here we are today.

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:18.080
As Mine and Julie have explained, and hopefully as everyone is getting so excited about, Quarto

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:21.320
builds on the learnings of the past decade.

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:27.360
It unifies teams across language boundaries and procedural differences.

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:33.039
And in the same vein, Quarto can also unify the way you consider building those books,

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:40.199
blogs, websites, or all sorts of other complex content, so you can focus on enabling users

00:03:40.199 --> 00:03:46.639
to discover, consume, and navigate in the ways that you would like to help them.

00:03:46.639 --> 00:03:52.160
And by doing so in a single, unified toolchain, it really does give you an unparalleled ability

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:59.679
to control the processing and ultimately the production of the content that you're working on.

00:03:59.679 --> 00:04:05.339
Now one thing that some of you may be thinking is, this seems like a lot.

00:04:05.339 --> 00:04:07.559
One tool that can do so much.

00:04:07.559 --> 00:04:12.479
How may I even start learning all of the things that it can do?

00:04:12.479 --> 00:04:18.480
So today, I'm going to do something that hopefully the presentation gods will be with me, and

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:23.200
I'm going to show you just how easy it is to get going with Quarto and do some pretty

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:24.480
cool stuff.

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:28.519
And hopefully also demonstrate about some of the thoughtfulness that the Quarto team

00:04:28.519 --> 00:04:34.679
has put into its design.

00:04:34.679 --> 00:04:42.679
So I switch over, so I can actually see what I'm typing.

00:04:42.679 --> 00:04:50.679
Oh, man, where's my mouse?

00:04:50.679 --> 00:04:55.679
Hoping that's going to give it back.

00:04:55.679 --> 00:04:56.679
All right.

00:04:56.679 --> 00:05:02.679
I want to mirror, and we're in business.

00:05:02.679 --> 00:05:04.679
All right.

00:05:04.679 --> 00:05:08.679
So, let's drop into RStudio.

00:05:09.679 --> 00:05:13.679
Now, one of the things that you can always do in RStudio is if you want to go play around

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:18.679
with a somewhat recent version of RStudio, you can go in, create a new directory, and

00:05:18.679 --> 00:05:21.679
Quarto is front and center.

00:05:21.679 --> 00:05:25.679
But the Quarto team has wanted to make sure that Quarto is available even if you're not

00:05:25.679 --> 00:05:29.679
using RStudio, if you're using VS Code or any other editor.

00:05:29.679 --> 00:05:35.679
And so many to all the things that you can do in the IDE, you can also do on the command line.

00:05:35.679 --> 00:05:39.679
In this case, we want to get going with a website.

00:05:39.679 --> 00:05:47.679
So in this case, I can, from the terminal, say Quarto, create project, type equals website.

00:05:47.679 --> 00:05:51.679
And what this is going to do is start me off with a scaffold.

00:05:51.679 --> 00:05:58.679
It has a couple of these QMD files that you've been hearing about, and it has this Quarto.yaml.

00:05:58.679 --> 00:06:04.679
This is the magic, the ability to say I have the area that I'm going to write my content,

00:06:04.679 --> 00:06:09.679
and I have a hub where I can control how I want that content to be rendered.

00:06:09.679 --> 00:06:15.679
So, if I want to take this content, maybe add a little bit more structure to it, so

00:06:15.679 --> 00:06:29.679
here is a header, and maybe we'll add a list, some markdown, some more interesting stuff,

00:06:29.679 --> 00:06:33.679
and I can render it.

00:06:33.679 --> 00:06:37.679
And what's going to pop up is my site.

00:06:37.679 --> 00:06:39.679
Now, let's look at this site really briefly.

00:06:39.679 --> 00:06:40.679
I have a title.

00:06:40.679 --> 00:06:44.679
I have a home and an about page.

00:06:44.679 --> 00:06:50.679
You can see my header that I can actually link to in case I want to get someone directly there if it's a longer page.

00:06:50.679 --> 00:06:57.679
And I even have a table of contents if I have more elements so I can see how I would navigate through that page.

00:06:57.679 --> 00:07:02.679
Now, you could go build this today in BlogDown, no problem.

00:07:02.679 --> 00:07:08.679
But where things start to get exciting to me in Quarto is just how flexible you can be when you say,

00:07:08.679 --> 00:07:11.679
what if I want to move things around?

00:07:11.679 --> 00:07:13.679
So, in this case, you can see how this is laid out.

00:07:13.679 --> 00:07:14.679
I have my website.

00:07:14.679 --> 00:07:16.679
I have a title that I can change.

00:07:16.679 --> 00:07:20.679
I also have a nav bar, so that top strip is a nav bar.

00:07:20.679 --> 00:07:26.679
But if I instead said I want to move my content so it's on the left, right, which is actually one of the big things

00:07:26.679 --> 00:07:29.679
that would differentiate for like a book, it's quite simple.

00:07:29.679 --> 00:07:33.679
I could just say this is a sidebar.

00:07:33.679 --> 00:07:35.679
And I want to take some contents.

00:07:35.679 --> 00:07:43.679
And if I go back here and I want to regenerate it, my site now has no nav bar,

00:07:43.679 --> 00:07:49.679
and instead my contents are on the side.

00:07:49.679 --> 00:07:52.679
You don't have to decide up front, is this a book?

00:07:52.679 --> 00:07:53.679
Is this a blog?

00:07:53.679 --> 00:07:57.679
Because Quarto is giving you the ability to put things in the way you want,

00:07:57.679 --> 00:08:01.679
and you can combine the ideas that make books great, blogs great,

00:08:01.679 --> 00:08:04.679
or any other different type of layout.

00:08:04.679 --> 00:08:13.679
And much of that is accessible directly with a couple lines of code in this configuration file.

00:08:13.679 --> 00:08:17.679
And so I'm going to bring back the nav bar for a little bit,

00:08:17.679 --> 00:08:22.679
and let's talk about blogs because I think that's one entry point for a lot of people

00:08:22.679 --> 00:08:25.679
where you can start to dabble with things that you're learning.

00:08:25.679 --> 00:08:27.679
Maybe it's stuff at the conferences.

00:08:27.679 --> 00:08:31.679
Maybe it's some of your own personal learnings that you want to put up to the world.

00:08:31.679 --> 00:08:36.679
And so what I want to do is I want to add some more organization to this content.

00:08:36.679 --> 00:08:40.679
And so I'm going to make a posts directory.

00:08:40.679 --> 00:08:46.679
And in that posts directory, I'm going to make a Quarto document.

00:08:46.679 --> 00:08:49.679
My first post.

00:08:49.679 --> 00:08:54.679
Now one of the things that you're going to see coming up right here is the visual editor.

00:08:54.679 --> 00:08:59.679
Now this isn't directly enabled only by Quarto,

00:08:59.679 --> 00:09:04.679
but this is something that to me is so exciting about the blend of what Quarto offers

00:09:04.679 --> 00:09:09.679
plus what the RStudio IDE can also bring to the table.

00:09:09.679 --> 00:09:14.679
So for some people, the ability to write markdown is fine for text,

00:09:14.679 --> 00:09:18.679
but as soon as you start doing more complex things like dealing with images,

00:09:18.679 --> 00:09:19.679
it becomes tedious to remember.

00:09:19.679 --> 00:09:20.679
Oh, what is that?

00:09:20.679 --> 00:09:23.679
Is it exclamation point bracket or is it parentheses?

00:09:23.679 --> 00:09:24.679
I can't keep track.

00:09:24.679 --> 00:09:25.679
How do I get stuff in?

00:09:25.679 --> 00:09:31.679
And suddenly going back to a Google Doc or something feels a lot more approachable.

00:09:31.679 --> 00:09:35.679
With Quarto and the visual editor, you get that what you see is what you get interface

00:09:35.679 --> 00:09:37.679
if you want that.

00:09:37.679 --> 00:09:40.679
Now I can always switch back to the source if I'm comfortable writing that,

00:09:40.679 --> 00:09:45.679
but the visual editor has some pretty nice goodies hidden inside of it.

00:09:45.679 --> 00:09:49.679
For example, if I wanted to clear all of this out,

00:09:49.679 --> 00:09:53.679
so let's just take this away real quick,

00:09:53.679 --> 00:09:56.679
and say I'm here at conf.

00:09:56.679 --> 00:10:03.679
RStudio has just rebranded.

00:10:03.679 --> 00:10:04.679
And you know what?

00:10:04.679 --> 00:10:09.679
I think it would be great to also add a screenshot.

00:10:09.679 --> 00:10:12.679
So I'm going to save this into my posts.

00:10:12.679 --> 00:10:19.679
I'm going to say my conference experience.

00:10:19.679 --> 00:10:24.679
And let's go over to the new Posit website.

00:10:24.679 --> 00:10:29.679
And for fun and games, I'm going to grab a little screenshot maybe.

00:10:29.679 --> 00:10:30.679
Boom.

00:10:30.679 --> 00:10:32.679
I grab that screenshot.

00:10:32.679 --> 00:10:34.679
I'm going to copy it to my clipboard.

00:10:34.679 --> 00:10:38.679
Now before the visual editor, I'd have to save this out.

00:10:38.679 --> 00:10:39.679
I'd have to put it in a directory.

00:10:39.679 --> 00:10:42.679
I'd have to move that around.

00:10:42.679 --> 00:10:46.679
I much prefer just pasting it.

00:10:46.679 --> 00:10:48.679
And the visual editor has now taken that

00:10:48.679 --> 00:10:52.679
and stuck it in an images directory for me.

00:10:52.679 --> 00:10:59.679
These quality of life improvements are all throughout the Corto ecosystem.

00:10:59.679 --> 00:11:01.679
To showcase another one real quick,

00:11:01.679 --> 00:11:04.679
if I look here and I wonder, you know, oh, what was it?

00:11:04.679 --> 00:11:05.679
Was it sidebar?

00:11:05.679 --> 00:11:06.679
Was it side something?

00:11:06.679 --> 00:11:08.679
I can start typing.

00:11:08.679 --> 00:11:13.679
And with some tab completion, it's going to tell me what my options are.

00:11:13.679 --> 00:11:17.679
Now notice, this isn't a long list of every possible option.

00:11:17.679 --> 00:11:22.679
It's just the options relevant for that level of indentation.

00:11:22.679 --> 00:11:24.679
In this case, I could say true or false.

00:11:24.679 --> 00:11:27.679
Or if I indent again and then ask and say,

00:11:27.679 --> 00:11:30.679
tell me what things I could do with the sidebar,

00:11:30.679 --> 00:11:32.679
you see this come up right here.

00:11:32.679 --> 00:11:35.679
And I can say, oh, yeah, I could put some contents in.

00:11:35.679 --> 00:11:37.679
The things that could frustrate you,

00:11:37.679 --> 00:11:40.679
make you feel like you needed to pull your hair out,

00:11:40.679 --> 00:11:43.679
the IDE in Corto and the tooling built around it

00:11:43.679 --> 00:11:46.679
is trying to help you not have to deal with that

00:11:46.679 --> 00:11:50.679
and be able to focus on your content.

00:11:50.679 --> 00:11:55.679
And so I have this first kind of conference experience page here.

00:11:55.679 --> 00:11:59.679
And what I'm going to do is I'm also going to go kind of steal,

00:11:59.679 --> 00:12:01.679
just for the sake of time,

00:12:01.679 --> 00:12:03.679
another kind of post starter

00:12:03.679 --> 00:12:06.679
that I grabbed right off of the Corto website.

00:12:06.679 --> 00:12:13.679
So we can also stick this in the posts page.

00:12:13.679 --> 00:12:16.679
All right.

00:12:16.679 --> 00:12:20.679
So what we have here is I've added

00:12:20.679 --> 00:12:25.679
another more complex Corto document

00:12:25.679 --> 00:12:28.679
that has a bunch more stuff going on to it.

00:12:29.679 --> 00:12:32.679
The majority of the intent of this doesn't matter so much.

00:12:32.679 --> 00:12:35.679
This is on the Corto website, so you can explore about it.

00:12:35.679 --> 00:12:39.679
But the point is I'm starting to build up multiple blog posts.

00:12:39.679 --> 00:12:42.679
And so how are you going to display those for your user?

00:12:42.679 --> 00:12:44.679
If we think about what a blog might have,

00:12:44.679 --> 00:12:46.679
you might have something that's sorted by date.

00:12:46.679 --> 00:12:49.679
It shows an author, maybe an image preview.

00:12:49.679 --> 00:12:53.679
It gives that stuff to you so you can see what's going on.

00:12:53.679 --> 00:12:57.679
And so instead of making it look like it's magical

00:12:57.679 --> 00:13:00.679
and I can remember how to do this off the top of my head,

00:13:00.679 --> 00:13:03.679
this is a great opportunity to go over to the Corto site

00:13:03.679 --> 00:13:06.679
to say, if this was the first time I was considering

00:13:06.679 --> 00:13:09.679
trying to build a blog and I wanted to go look at it,

00:13:09.679 --> 00:13:12.679
I can go and look through the search,

00:13:12.679 --> 00:13:15.679
and Corto is going to give you

00:13:15.679 --> 00:13:17.679
a whole bunch of information on that site

00:13:17.679 --> 00:13:19.679
about what to do for blogging.

00:13:19.679 --> 00:13:22.679
And so in this case, I can scroll down a little bit,

00:13:22.679 --> 00:13:25.679
and they say, hey, if you are dealing with a blog,

00:13:25.679 --> 00:13:28.679
you can grab this, and what we can see here

00:13:28.679 --> 00:13:31.679
is the idea of some configuration

00:13:31.679 --> 00:13:33.679
that allows us to say,

00:13:33.679 --> 00:13:35.679
you're going to want to display some listings,

00:13:35.679 --> 00:13:37.679
you have some content that's going to be

00:13:37.679 --> 00:13:39.679
a bunch of different post, you know,

00:13:39.679 --> 00:13:41.679
QMD documents or otherwise, and you're probably

00:13:41.679 --> 00:13:43.679
going to want to do something with this.

00:13:43.679 --> 00:13:46.679
So let's just steal this right from the site.

00:13:46.679 --> 00:13:49.679
I'm going to make a new document.

00:13:49.679 --> 00:13:53.679
And we're just going to come in.

00:13:54.679 --> 00:13:56.679
We're going to clear it all out,

00:13:56.679 --> 00:13:58.679
and I'm just going to paste this in.

00:13:58.679 --> 00:14:00.679
So we'll call this the blog.

00:14:00.679 --> 00:14:02.679
Save it.

00:14:02.679 --> 00:14:06.679
And in the top, we'll call this the blog.

00:14:06.679 --> 00:14:09.679
Make sure I get it in the right spot.

00:14:09.679 --> 00:14:11.679
All right.

00:14:11.679 --> 00:14:14.679
So now I have this blog QMD file,

00:14:14.679 --> 00:14:16.679
and I just have to say where I want it to be.

00:14:16.679 --> 00:14:18.679
In this case, I'd be completely fine

00:14:18.679 --> 00:14:21.679
with it being right next to that home and that about,

00:14:21.679 --> 00:14:25.679
so I'll say text is blog,

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:31.679
and href is blog.qmd.

00:14:33.679 --> 00:14:37.679
Now notice the contents is this posts folder.

00:14:37.679 --> 00:14:39.679
If I had a different folder name,

00:14:39.679 --> 00:14:41.679
I'd give it a different thing.

00:14:41.679 --> 00:14:43.679
So now let's go check

00:14:43.679 --> 00:14:46.679
at what this whole site is going to look like.

00:14:47.679 --> 00:14:49.679
So everything got rendered.

00:14:49.679 --> 00:14:51.679
I can go to my about page.

00:14:51.679 --> 00:14:53.679
I can go to my blog,

00:14:53.679 --> 00:14:55.679
and you can see here that I have these pages

00:14:55.679 --> 00:14:57.679
that I can click in,

00:14:57.679 --> 00:15:00.679
and I already have a pretty great-looking thing

00:15:00.679 --> 00:15:02.679
right out of the box

00:15:02.679 --> 00:15:04.679
that shows all sorts of information about it.

00:15:04.679 --> 00:15:06.679
You can see the author, the publication date,

00:15:06.679 --> 00:15:10.679
and a whole bunch of images.

00:15:10.679 --> 00:15:14.679
Now, content is great looking at it on your laptop.

00:15:15.679 --> 00:15:17.679
But realistically, the true excitement

00:15:17.679 --> 00:15:20.679
is when you can actually get this out to the world.

00:15:20.679 --> 00:15:23.679
And so the Quarto team has also wanted to make sure

00:15:23.679 --> 00:15:26.679
they could make this as easy as possible for everyone.

00:15:26.679 --> 00:15:28.679
And so I'm going to come in here.

00:15:28.679 --> 00:15:31.679
I did notice as I was copying things around,

00:15:31.679 --> 00:15:33.679
I blew away that old Posit image,

00:15:33.679 --> 00:15:37.679
so let me go clean that kind of broken link up real quick.

00:15:37.679 --> 00:15:39.679
I saw the error flash around,

00:15:39.679 --> 00:15:42.679
so if I go into my images post,

00:15:43.679 --> 00:15:46.679
that copy-paste of the starter killed it off,

00:15:46.679 --> 00:15:48.679
so I want to save that real quick.

00:15:48.679 --> 00:15:50.679
So here I am.

00:15:50.679 --> 00:15:52.679
I want to get this to the world,

00:15:52.679 --> 00:15:56.679
so let's go back to the Quarto command line.

00:15:56.679 --> 00:16:00.679
In this case, I can say...

00:16:00.679 --> 00:16:02.679
Quarto publish.

00:16:02.679 --> 00:16:04.679
And there are a number of different endpoints.

00:16:04.679 --> 00:16:07.679
If you use RStudio Connect, that is, of course, one of them.

00:16:07.679 --> 00:16:10.679
There's Netlify, if you've ever heard of Netlify.

00:16:10.679 --> 00:16:16.679
But one other thing that I'm so excited to show is Quarto Pubs.

00:16:16.679 --> 00:16:19.679
And in this case, I can say,

00:16:19.679 --> 00:16:21.679
I would absolutely like to publish.

00:16:21.679 --> 00:16:24.679
I have a site that by default is going to be the folder name,

00:16:24.679 --> 00:16:27.679
but I can give it any name I want.

00:16:27.679 --> 00:16:29.679
And up it goes.

00:16:29.679 --> 00:16:32.679
It's uploading all of the elements to the site.

00:16:32.679 --> 00:16:36.679
It's deploying it.

00:16:37.679 --> 00:16:39.679
And in just a moment,

00:16:39.679 --> 00:16:43.679
